{{nihongo|'''Ayase Ueda'''|上田 綺世|Ueda Ayase|born 28 August 1998}} is a Japanese professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[striker (association football)|striker]] for [[Eredivisie]] club [[Feyenoord]] and the [[Japan national football team|Japan national team]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=上田 綺世：鹿島アントラーズ：Ｊリーグ.jp |url=https://www.jleague.jp/player/1615529/#attack |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525200843/https://www.jleague.jp/player/1615529/#attack |archive-date=25 May 2019 |access-date=25 May 2019}}</ref>

==Youth career==
Born in the city of [[Mito, Ibaraki|Mito]], located in the [[Ibaraki Prefecture]], he began playing football at age 6 and was inspired by seeing his father score a [[hat-trick]] in a match.<ref name="Tokyo 2020 profile">{{cite web |title=Football UEDA Ayase |url=https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/athlete-profile-n1329493-ueda-ayase.htm |work=Tokyo 2020 Olympics |publisher=[[Tokyo Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]] |access-date=19 August 2021 |language=en-us |archive-date=19 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210819194357/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/athlete-profile-n1329493-ueda-ayase.htm |url-status=dead }}</ref> Ueda began his youth career with Kashima Antlers Norte whilst at junior high school and then moved on to play at Kashima Gakuen High School.<ref>{{cite web |title=鹿島が見逃した逸材!? 法政大に35年ぶりの総理大臣杯をもたらした１年生ストライカー {{!}} サッカーダイジェストWeb |url=https://www.soccerdigestweb.com/news/detail2/id=29877 |website=www.soccerdigestweb.com |language=ja}}</ref> He represented his high school in both the [[Football at the Inter High School Sports Festival|Inter High School Championship]] and the [[All Japan High School Soccer Tournament]] – he scored two goals in the first round of the competition<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2016-17 Japan Highschool Soccer Tournament 16/12/31 Kashima Gakuen High School - Takagawa Gakuen High School Results, Players, Formation |url=https://soccer-db.net/result.php?g=20161231903&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=7 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref> but the team were knocked out in the second round.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2016 Ayase Ueda Result by Season |url=https://soccer-db.net/player/index.php?pl=62982&yr=2016&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=7 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

===Hosei University===
After graduating high school, Ueda then went on to study Sport Studies at [[Hosei University]] and he was part of the football team right from his first year. In his first year at Hosei, Ueda scored 15 goals in 27 games and won the JUFA Kanto League 1 Best Rookie award.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2017 Ayase Ueda Result by Season |url=https://soccer-db.net/player/index.php?pl=62982&yr=2017&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref> In his second year, Ueda helped Hosei University win the All Japan University Football Championship for the first time in 42 years.<ref>{{cite web |title=歴代優勝チーム一覧｜2019年度 第68回全日本大学サッカー選手権大会｜JFA.jp |url=http://www.jfa.jp/match/alljapan_university_2019/history.html |access-date=17 May 2021 |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=20 February 2019 |title=「いつか戻ってやる」 鹿島加入内定の法政大FW上田綺世、中学時代の挫折に誓った決意 |url=https://www.football-zone.net/archives/171481 |access-date=17 May 2021 |website=www.football-zone.net |language=ja}}</ref> He scored in the semi-final against [[Juntendo University]] and scored 2 goals in the tournament overall, where he was also selected as the Best Forward in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2018 Japan Inter College Tournament 18/12/19 Juntendo University - Hosei University Results, Players |url=https://soccer-db.net/result.php?g=20181219061&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref> In the 2018 JUFA Kanto League 1, he was also inducted into the season's Best XI after scoring 11 goals in 19 appearances.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2018 JUFA Kanto League 1 |url=https://soccer-db.net/competition/index.php?comp=1065&yr=2018&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

After the success of his first two years at university, in February 2019 it was announced that he would be joining his boyhood club [[Kashima Antlers]] as a [[J.League designated special players|designated special player]], with a view to join the club fully in 2021.<ref>{{cite web |author1=FromOne co., Ltd |date=12 February 2019 |title=U21代表FW上田綺世、21年の鹿島加入が内定！ 東京五輪のエース候補 |url=https://www.soccer-king.jp/news/japan/jl/20190212/905851.html |access-date=17 May 2021 |website=サッカーキング |language=ja}}</ref> He began the season back representing Hosei, but in July 2019 it was announced that he would be retiring from the university team and would be joining Kashima earlier than initially planned.<ref>{{cite web |title=上田選手の加入について {{!}} 鹿島アントラーズ オフィシャルサイト |url=https://www.antlers.co.jp/news/release/72728 |website=鹿島アントラーズ オフィシャルサイト {{!}} KASHIMA ANTLERS |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> His national team call up accelerated his departure from the university team and provided him with an opportunity to take the next step – Ueda saying "I have done what I can do in Hosei".<ref>{{cite web |title=なぜ、このタイミングとなったのか…"前倒し"で鹿島加入のFW上田綺世「コパの結果がきっかけではない」 |url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?280436-280436-fl |website=ゲキサカ |date=26 July 2019 |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=ja}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Kashima Antlers===
He made his debut for Kashima Antlers in July 2019, coming on as a late substitute for [[Shoma Doi]] in a 1–1 league draw with [[Urawa Red Diamonds]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Urawa Reds vs. Kashima Antlers - 31 July 2019 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/07/31/japan/j1-league/urawa-red-diamonds/kashima-antlers/3023768/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=17 May 2021}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal the following month, in a 2–1 league victory over [[Yokohama F. Marinos]].<ref>{{cite web |title=鹿島新加入・上田綺世のＪ初ゴールが決勝点！「こんな大勢の人に名前を呼んでもらえて感動しています」 {{!}} サッカーダイジェストWeb |url=https://www.soccerdigestweb.com/news/detail/id=62662 |website=www.soccerdigestweb.com |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kashima Antlers vs. Yokohama F. Marinos - 10 August 2019 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/08/10/japan/j1-league/kashima-antlers/yokohama-f-marinos/2973078/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=17 May 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=【公式】ハイライト：鹿島アントラーズvs横浜Ｆ・マリノス 明治安田生命Ｊ１リーグ 第22節 2019/8/10 | website=[[YouTube]] | date=10 August 2019 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KWHCkDTDID8&feature=emb_logo |access-date=17 May 2021 |language=en}}</ref> On his first start for the club in September, he scored two goals in a 4–0 league win against [[Shimizu S-Pulse]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Shimizu S-Pulse vs. Kashima Antlers - 1 September 2019 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/09/01/japan/j1-league/shimizu-s-pulse/kashima-antlers/2973104/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=19 May 2021}}</ref> He ended his debut season with 4 league goals in less than 400 minutes. Ueda also made his first appearances in a continental competition, appearing in both games against [[Guangzhou F.C.]] in the quarter final of the [[2019 AFC Champions League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Guangzhou FC vs. Kashima Antlers - 28 August 2019 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/08/28/asia/afc-champions-league/guangzhou-yiyao/kashima-antlers/2942587/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=19 May 2021}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Kashima Antlers vs. Guangzhou FC - 18 September 2019 |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/09/18/asia/afc-champions-league/kashima-antlers/guangzhou-yiyao/2942588/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=19 May 2021}}</ref>

After a successful debut season, Ueda continued to make an impression in the 2020 season scoring 10 goals in 29 appearances across all competitions – made even more impressive by the fact he only played the full 90 minutes in two games all season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Soccer D.B. : 2020 Ayase Ueda Result by Season |url=https://soccer-db.net/player/index.php?pl=62982&yr=2020&la=e |website=Soccer D.B. |access-date=3 June 2021 |language=en}}</ref>

In the 2021 season, Ueda's goals were vital to Kashima's top 4 finish. In 29 league games, he scored 14 goals making him Kashima's top goalscorer for the season and the fourth highest goalscorer in the league.<ref>{{cite web |title=Summary - J1 League - Japan - Results, fixtures, tables and news |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/national/japan/j1-league/2021/regular-season/r61498/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=30 December 2021}}</ref> This was in spite of him missing almost two months of football after suffering a groin strain in June.<ref>{{cite web |title=「焦りはない」 リハビリ中のFW上田綺世、五輪初戦の復帰へ「順調に進んでいる」（Football ZONE web） |url=https://news.yahoo.co.jp/articles/5d3983174cb8251e9693a0d84e9affc950931319 |website=Yahoo!ニュース |access-date=30 December 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> His performances did not go unrewarded and was named one of the 31 Outstanding J.League players as voted for by managers and players, although he did not make it into the eventual overall [[J.League Best XI|Best XI]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jリーグ優秀選手31名が決定! 6日のJリーグアウォーズでMVP&ベストイレブンが発表 |url=https://web.gekisaka.jp/news/detail/?346939-346939-fl |website=ゲキサカ |date=5 December 2021 |access-date=30 December 2021 |language=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2021シーズンのJリーグ優秀選手賞31名発表 {{!}} Goal.com |url=https://www.goal.com/jp/%E3%83%8B%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B9/jleague-j1-player-20211430/blt8c5913b435f0053a |website=www.goal.com |access-date=30 December 2021}}</ref>

In 2022, he scored a brace against Gamba Osaka in what was Kashima's first official match of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jleague.co/match/j1/2022021904/overview/|title=Gamba v Kashima|access-date=1 July 2022}}</ref> Since then, he improved his goalscoring status, finishing as the [[2022 J1 League]] topscorer in June, having scored 10 goals in 18 matches. In his already outstanding previous year, he needed 21 matches to score his 10 goals. And in 2022, he only needed 16 matches to match this goal tally. He also won Moriyasu's trust, and was frequently called up for the national team, having participated in 5 out of the 6 matches the national team played in from March to June. After this improvement in club performances, alongside more game-time with the national team, he secured a transfer to a European club.

===Cercle Brugge===
[[File:AyaseUedaFrontPriorMatchCercleVsOHV (cropped).jpg|thumb|259x259px|Ueda with [[Cercle Brugge KSV|Cercle Brugge]] in 2022]]
On 1 July 2022, Ueda was signed by [[Cercle Brugge KSV|Cercle Brugge]] on a four-season contract lasting until June 2026.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.antlers.co.jp/news/release/88562|title=上田選手のサークル・ブルージュKSV完全移籍合意|trans-title=Agreement on Ayase Ueda's transfer to Cercle Brugge|language=ja|publisher=Kashima Antlers|access-date=1 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220701010054/https://www.antlers.co.jp/news/release/88562|archive-date=1 July 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cerclebrugge.be/nl/news/princiepsakkoord-ayase-ueda-naar-cercle-brugge|title=Princiepsakkoord: Ayase Ueda naar Cercle Brugge|language=nl|publisher=Cercle Brugge|access-date=1 July 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220920173113/https://www.cerclebrugge.be/nl/news/princiepsakkoord-ayase-ueda-naar-cercle-brugge|archive-date=20 September 2022}}</ref> He made his debut in a 2–0 league defeat to [[K.V.C. Westerlo|Westerlo]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Westerlo vs. Cercle Brugge - 24 July 2022 |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/07/24/belgium/pro-league/kvc-westerlo/cercle-brugge-ksv/3807751/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=8 August 2023}}</ref> He had to wait until his sixth game before scoring his first goal for the club, netting in a 1–1 league draw with [[S.V. Zulte Waregem|Zulte Waregem]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ayase Ueda and Shinji Kagawa on target in Belgium |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2022/08/28/soccer/belgium-ueda-kagawa-goals/ |website=The Japan Times |access-date=8 August 2023 |language=en |date=28 August 2022}}</ref> Before Ueda joined up with the rest of the Japan squad to participate in the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in November, he had scored eight goals in eighteen games, including a brace and a man of the match performance in a 4–1 victory over [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=KW |first1=Redactie |title=Matchrapport Cercle Brugge: Ayase Ueda draagt met twee goals bij tot een derde winst op rij |url=https://kw.be/sport/voetbal/jupiler-pro-league-profs-1a/matchrapport-cercle-brugge-ayase-ueda-draagt-met-twee-goals-bij-tot-een-derde-winst-op-rij/ |website=KW.be |access-date=8 August 2023 |language=nl |date=23 October 2022}}</ref> In the second half of the season, Ueda continued his goal-scoring form and finished the regular season with 18 league goals, making him the joint-second highest scorer in the league.<ref>{{cite web |title=Summary - First Division A - Belgium - Results, fixtures, tables and news |url=https://int.soccerway.com/national/belgium/pro-league/20222023/regular-season/r70296/ |website=Soccerway |access-date=8 August 2023}}</ref> Ueda finished the season with 23 goals in 42 appearances across all competitions and was runner-up in Cercle Brugge's Player of the Season vote to [[Thibo Somers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thibo Somers is jullie 'Player of the Season' |url=https://www.cerclebrugge.be/news/articles/somers-pots |website=www.cerclebrugge.be |access-date=8 August 2023 |language=nl}}</ref>

===Feyenoord===
On 3 August 2023, Ueda signed a five-year contract with Dutch champions [[Feyenoord]] for a fee of €8 million. He was given the number 9 shirt.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vi.nl/nieuws/feyenoord-haalt-japanse-smaakmaker-ueda-binnen-1 |title=Feyenoord haalt Japanse smaakmaker Ueda binnen |trans-title=Feyenoord brings in Japanese playmaker Ueda |language=Dutch |date=3 August 2023 |access-date=3 August 2023}}</ref> 
He made his debut in 0–0 league draw with [[Fortuna Sittard]] in the opening game of the season, after coming on as a second-half substitute for [[Quilindschy Hartman]].<ref>{{cite web |title=上田綺世がフェイエノールトデビュー！開幕節フォルトゥナ戦で76分に投入 {{!}} Goal.com 日本 |url=https://www.goal.com/jp/%E3%83%8B%E3%83%A5%E3%83%BC%E3%82%B9/Ayase-ueda-debut-feyenoord-20230813/blt186d12a34de5023f |website=www.goal.com |access-date=25 August 2023 |language=ja |date=13 August 2023}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 3 September, scoring the fourth goal in a 5–1 away win against [[FC Utrecht]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ad.nl/nederlands-voetbal/feyenoord-heerst-in-galgenwaard-en-drukt-fc-utrecht-nog-dieper-in-het-moeras~a9b016bc/ |title=Feyenoord heerst in Galgenwaard en drukt FC Utrecht nog dieper in het moeras |trans-title=Feyenoord rules in the Galgenward and further brings FC Utrecht into trouble |language=Dutch |date=3 September 2023 |access-date=3 September 2022}}</ref>

Ueda made his [[2023–24 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] debut in October 2023, in a 3–2 defeat to [[Atlético Madrid]]. He played 60 minutes before being substituted, in what was his first start for the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Atlético 3-2 Feyenoord (4 Oct, 2023) Game Analysis - ESPN (UK) |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/687561 |website=ESPN |access-date=1 January 2025 |language=en}}</ref>
Due to the form of teammate [[Santiago Giménez]], Ueda was largely used as a substitute in his debut season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Why is young star Santiago Gimenez scoring for Feyenoord but not Mexico? |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/39330220/why-santiago-gimenez-scoring-feyenoord-not-mexico |website=ESPN.com |access-date=1 January 2025 |language=en |date=20 January 2024}}</ref> On 21 April 2024, he came off the bench in a 1–0 win over [[NEC Nijmegen]] in the [[2024 KNVB Cup final|KNVB Cup final]] to help Feyenoord clinch their fourteenth KNVB Cup title.<ref name="knvb-cup-win-23-24">{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2517666-als-rook-is-opgetrokken-wint-feyenoord-bekerfinale-van-nec |title=Als rook is opgetrokken, wint Feyenoord bekerfinale van NEC |trans-title=As smoke clears, Feyenoord wins cup final against NEC |language=Dutch |date=21 April 2024 |access-date=21 April 2024}}</ref> In his debut season, he scored 5 goals in 26 league appearances (with only 5 games as a starter) as the team finished second in the league.

At the start of the 2024–25 season, Ueda won his second trophy with the club after Feyenoord beat [[PSV Eindhoven]] in the [[2024 Johan Cruyff Shield]]. As the match went to a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] after a 4–4 draw, Ueda scored Feyenoord's second spot-kick and secured a 4–2 win.<ref>{{cite web |title=Feyenoord edge PSV on penalties to win season-opening Johan Cruyff Shield {{!}} Flashscore.com.gh |url=https://www.flashscore.com.gh/news/soccer-johan-cruyff-shield-feyenoord-edge-psv-on-penalties-to-win-season-opening-johan-cruyff-shield/fNYn2yhI/ |website=www.flashscore.com.gh |access-date=1 January 2025 |language=en-GH}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=PSV vs. Feyenoord - 4 August 2024 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2024/08/04/netherlands/super-cup/psv-nv/feyenoord-rotterdam-nv/4368593/ |website=int.soccerway.com |access-date=1 January 2025 |language=en}}</ref>

In September 2024, he scored his first goal of the 2024–25 campaign in a 2–0 league win over [[NAC Breda]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Feyenoord vs. NAC Breda - 22 September 2024 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2024/09/22/netherlands/eredivisie/feyenoord-rotterdam-nv/nac-bv/4367994/ |website=int.soccerway.com |access-date=1 January 2025 |language=en}}</ref> On 23 October, Ueda scored his first goal in a Champions League game, scoring the first goal in a 3–1 victory over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Benfica 1-3 Feyenoord: Dutch side hold on to win in Champions League |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c4g0nzynl5gt?page=4 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=1 January 2025}}</ref> Just as Ueda was starting more games, he sustained a hamstring injury in a Eredivise game against Ajax in early November, which would rule him out for the remainder of 2024.<ref>{{cite web |title=Blow for Japan as Ueda ruled out for rest of 2024 |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/blow-japan-ueda-ruled-out-rest-2024-2024-11-05/ |website=reuters.com |access-date=1 January 2025 |date=5 November 2024}}</ref>

On 6 December 2025, he scored four goals in a 6–1 victory over [[PEC Zwolle]], bringing his tally to 18 goals in 15 matches in the [[2025–26 Eredivisie|2025–26 season]], which marked his best scoring run ever in the Eredivisie.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nu.nl/voetbal/6378575/feyenoord-dendert-mede-door-vier-doelpunten-ueda-over-pec-heen-in-de-kuip.html |title=Feyenoord heeft zaterdag mede door vier goals van Ayase Ueda met grote cijfers gewonnen van PEC Zwolle. De Rotterdammers wonnen het Eredivisie-duel met 6-1 in De Kuip |publisher=nu.nl |language=nl |date=6 December 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth career===
In November 2017 whilst still at Hosei University, Ueda received his first national team call up to represent the [[Japan national under-20 football team|U-20]] team at the friendly [[2017 M-150 Cup|M-150 Cup]] competition.<ref>{{cite web |title=U-20 Japan National Team squad, schedule – Thailand tour (6–17 Dec.) [M-150 CUP 2017] |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u20_2017/M-150_cup_2017/news/00015655/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=8 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> He made his first appearance as a substitute in a 2–1 defeat to [[Thailand national under-23 football team|Thailand]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixtures/Results {{!}} M-150 CUP 2017 {{!}} Japan Football Association |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u20_2017/M-150_cup_2017/match_page/m1.html |website=jfa.jp |access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref> but scored twice on his first start in a 4–0 win over [[North Korea national under-23 football team|North Korea]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ญี่ปุ่น U23 คืนฟอร์มทุบเกาหลีเหนือ U23 4–0 ศึก M-150 คัพ |url=http://fathailand.org/news/1633 |website=fathailand.org |access-date=8 June 2021 |language=th}}</ref> Japan played [[Uzbekistan national under-23 football team|Uzbekistan]] in the final where Ueda played the whole game which ended in a 2–2 draw and was decided on penalties.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixtures/Results {{!}} M-150 CUP 2017 {{!}} Japan Football Association |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u20_2017/M-150_cup_2017/match_page/m3.html |website=jfa.jp |access-date=8 June 2021}}</ref> Ueda missed Japan's final penalty in the shootout to hand the tournament victory to Uzbekistan.<ref>{{cite web |title=อุซเบกิสถาน U23 แม่นโทษชนะญี่ปุ่น U23 6–5 (2–2) คว้าแชมป์ M-150 คัพ |url=http://fathailand.org/news/1658 |website=fathailand.org |access-date=8 June 2021 |language=th |archive-date=25 December 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211225203028/http://fathailand.org/news/1658 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

In June 2018, Ueda was part of the Japan U-21 squad to play in the prestigious [[2018 Toulon Tournament|Toulon Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=U-21 Japan National Team squad, schedule – the 46th Toulon International Tournament (5/28-6/9) |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/news/00017533/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=13 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> Used as a substitute in the first two group games against [[Turkey national under-20 football team|Turkey]] and [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal]], he made a big impact in the latter scoring two goals as Japan won 3–2.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixtures/Results│The 46th Toulon Tournament 2018｜Japan National Teams｜JFA｜Japan Football Association |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/toulontournament_2018/match_page/m11.html |website=jfa.jp |access-date=13 June 2021}}</ref>

Ueda was also part of the silver medal-winning squad from the [[2018 Asian Games]] squad in August.<ref>{{cite web |title=U-21 Japan National Team squad, schedule – The 18th Asian Games 2018 Jakarta Palembang (8/14-9/1) |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/news/00018306/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=20 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> He appeared in six out of Japan's seven games during the tournament, including playing the full 120 minutes against [[South Korea national under-23 football team|South Korea]] in their extra time win in the gold medal match.<ref>{{cite web |title=Korea Republic U23 vs. Japan U23 – 1 September 2018 – Soccerway |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2018/09/01/asia/asian-games/korea-republic-u23/japan-u23/2869283/ |website=uk.soccerway.com |access-date=20 June 2021}}</ref> Ueda scored three goals in the tournament, firstly a penalty in Japan's 1–0 Round of 16 win against [[Malaysia national under-23 football team|Malaysia]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan squeeze through, heartbreak for Malaysia {{!}} Football {{!}} News {{!}} |url=https://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/japan-squeeze-through-heartbreak-for-malaysia |website=the-AFC |access-date=20 June 2021}}</ref> then in the 1-0 semi-final win over the [[United Arab Emirates national under-23 football team|United Arab Emirates]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Super sub Ueda sends Japan to decider {{!}} Football {{!}} News {{!}} |url=https://www.the-afc.com/news/afcsection/super-sub-ueda-sends-japan-to-decider |website=the-AFC |access-date=20 June 2021}}</ref> with the final goal coming during extra time of the gold medal match.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Korea beat Japan in Asian Games final as Heung-Min Son earns national service exemption |url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/south-korea-beat-japan-in-asian-games-final-as-heung-min-son-earns-national-service-exemption_sto6912691/story.shtml |website=Eurosport |access-date=20 June 2021 |language=en |date=1 September 2018}}</ref>

Ueda also took part in the U-23 Dubai Cup for Japan U-21s in November 2018. He ended up as top scorer in the tournament, scoring a hat-trick in a 5–0 win over [[Kuwait national under-23 football team|Kuwait]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixtures/Results│Dubai Cup U-23｜Japan National Teams｜JFA｜Japan Football Association |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/dubaicup_u23_2018/match_page/m4.html |website=jfa.jp |access-date=16 June 2021}}</ref> and the equalising goal in a 1–1 draw with [[United Arab Emirates national under-23 football team|United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixtures/Results│Dubai Cup U-23｜Japan National Teams｜JFA｜Japan Football Association |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/dubaicup_u23_2018/match_page/m5.html |website=jfa.jp |access-date=16 June 2021}}</ref> Japan finished in second place in the tournament and Ueda was named most valuable player.<ref>{{cite web |title=U-21 Japan National Team draws with UAE to finish in second place at Dubai Cup U-23 on UAE Tour (11/11-21) |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u21_2018/dubaicup_u23_2018/news/00019625/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=16 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref>

In 2019, Ueda continued to play for the U-23 squad, this time in the [[2020 AFC U-23 Championship qualification|AFC U-23 Championship qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite web |title=U-22 Japan National Team squad, schedule – AFC U-23 Championship Thailand 2020 Qualifiers (3/22-26 ＠Myanmar) |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/news/00020740/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=21 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> Japan cruised through their qualifying group, scoring 21 goals and conceding none. He scored a hat-trick in an 8–0 win over [[Macau national under-23 football team|Macau]]<ref>{{cite web |title=AFCS |url=http://stats.the-afc.com/match_report/14567 |website=stats.the-afc.com |access-date=21 June 2021}}</ref> and scored another in a 6–0 win over [[Timor-Leste national under-23 football team|Timor-Leste]].<ref>{{cite web |title=AFCS |url=http://stats.the-afc.com/match_report/14570 |website=stats.the-afc.com |access-date=21 June 2021}}</ref> In the main competition, Japan were surprisingly knocked out at the group stage, with Ueda not able to make an impact in either of the games he appeared in.<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan Makes Shock Exit From 2020 AFC U23 Championship {{!}} pelisterfc.com |url=https://pelisterfc.com/japan-makes-shock-exit-from-2020-afc-u23-championship/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200930204515/https://pelisterfc.com/japan-makes-shock-exit-from-2020-afc-u23-championship/ |url-status=usurped |archive-date=30 September 2020 |access-date=24 June 2021}}</ref>

In July 2019, Ueda was part of the Japan team to take part in the biannual [[2019 Summer Universiade|Summer Universiade]]. He scored two goals in the first game of the competition in a 3–0 victory over [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan Universiade National Team wins over Argentina 3–0 at the 30th Summer Universiade Napoli 2019 |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/university_2019/news/00021982/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=5 July 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> After seeing off South Korea in the quarter finals and beating Italy on penalties in the semi-final, Japan ended up winning the competition after a 4–1 victory over Brazil in the gold medal match including a hat-trick from Ueda.<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan outclass Brazil to take men's football gold |url=https://www.fisu.net/news/football/japan-outclass-brazil-to-take-men-s-football-gold |website=fisu.net |access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref>

In June 2021, Ueda was named in Japan's squad to play at the delayed [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite web |title=U-24 Japan National Team Squad – Games of the XXXII Olympiad (Tokyo 2020)【7/21-8/7】, KIRIN CHALLENGE CUP 2021【7/12＠Osaka, 7/17＠Hyogo】 |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/u24_2021/news/00027265/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=5 July 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> He went on to make an appearance at every game during the tournament, including 90 minutes in a 4–0 win over [[France Olympic football team|France]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Football – France vs Japan – Group A Results |url=https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpa-000500-.htm |work=Tokyo 2020 Olympics |publisher=[[Tokyo Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]] |access-date=19 August 2021 |language=en-us |archive-date=10 August 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210810101742/https://olympics.com/tokyo-2020/olympic-games/en/results/football/results-men-gpa-000500-.htm |url-status=dead }}</ref> and culminated in Japan finishing fourth after losing the bronze medal match 3–1 to [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexico]].<ref name="Tokyo 2020 profile" />

===Senior career===
After showing a high goalscoring form for Japan's youth teams, on 24 May 2019, Ueda was called up by [[Japan national football team|Japan]]'s head coach [[Hajime Moriyasu]] to feature in the [[2019 Copa América|Copa América]] played in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jfa.jp/eng/news/00021323/|title=SAMURAI BLUE (Japan National Team) Squad, Schedule – CONMEBOL Copa America Brazil 2019 (6/14–7/7)|publisher=JFA|date=24 May 2019}}</ref> At the time of his call-up, he was still playing for his university team, the first time a university player was called up since [[Kensuke Nagai]] and [[Kazuya Yamamura]] were selected in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=法政大FW上田綺世、日本代表メンバー初招集。大学生A代表は9年半ぶり！ |url=https://www.footballchannel.jp/2019/05/24/post322917/ |website=フットボールチャンネル |date=24 May 2019 |access-date=24 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> He made his debut on 17 June 2019 in a 4–0 defeat against [[Chile national football team|Chile]], as a starter.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[CONMEBOL]]|url=http://estadisticas.conmebol.com/html/v3/index.html?channel=deportes.futbol.copaamerica.462516&lang=es_LA|title=Japan v Chile game report|date=17 June 2019}}</ref> He went on to make two more appearances as a substitute in the competition, before Japan were knocked out at the group stage with Ueda missing some big chances throughout.<ref>{{cite web |title="唯一の大学生"上田綺世が不名誉記録…「決定機でのミス」がコパ・アメリカ最多に {{!}} サッカーダイジェストWeb |url=https://www.soccerdigestweb.com/news/detail/id=60596 |website=soccerdigestweb.com |access-date=24 June 2021 |language=ja}}</ref>

Despite his performances at Copa América, Moriyasu once again named Ueda in the Japan squad, this time for the [[2019 EAFF E-1 Football Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |title=SAMURAI BLUE (Japan National Team) Squad, Schedule – EAFF E-1 Football Championship 2019 Final (12/10-18 ＠Korea Republic) |url=https://www.jfa.jp/eng/national_team/EAFF_E1_Football_Championship_2019/news/00023750/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=5 July 2021 |language=ja}}</ref> He appeared in all three of Japan's games and played his first full 90 minutes in a senior international in a 2–1 victory over [[China national football team|China PR]].<ref>{{cite web |title=China PR vs. Japan – 10 December 2019 – Soccerway |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2019/12/10/asia/east-asian-football-championship/china-pr/japan/2961762/ |website=uk.soccerway.com |access-date=5 July 2021}}</ref> Japan finished runners-up in the tournament after a 1–0 defeat to [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in the final.<ref>{{cite web |title=SAMURAI BLUE finish as runners-up with loss against Korea Republic – EAFF E-1 Football Championship |url=http://jfa.jp/eng/samuraiblue/news/00023968/ |website=JFA｜公益財団法人日本サッカー協会 |access-date=5 July 2021 |language=ja}}</ref>

In November 2022, Ueda was called up to Japan's squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Orlowitz |first1=Dan |title=Hajime Moriyasu announces Japan squad for World Cup |url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2022/11/01/soccer/international-soccer/japan-2022-world-cup-squad/ |website=The Japan Times |access-date=1 November 2022 |date=1 November 2022 |archive-date=30 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221130053153/https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2022/11/01/soccer/international-soccer/japan-2022-world-cup-squad/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> He made his World Cup debut when starting in Japan's second group game against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]], however Ueda struggled to make an impact on the game and was substituted at half-time for [[Takuma Asano]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Japan vs. Costa Rica – Football Match Report – November 27, 2022 – ESPN |url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/report/_/gameId/633813 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=7 February 2023 |language=en |date=27 November 2022}}</ref> Japan went on to lose the game 1–0 to a late Costa Rica winner. This was Ueda's first and last appearance at the 2022 World Cup as he was then unused for the rest of the tournament, as Japan got knocked out in the Round of 16 by eventual semi-finalists [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]].

On 15 June 2023, Ueda scored his first senior international goal in a 6–0 thrashing of [[El Salvador national football team|El Salvador]] in the [[Kirin Cup Soccer#2023 Kirin Challenge Cup|2023 Kirin Challenge Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=NEWS |first1=KYODO |title=Football: Japan thrash 10-man El Salvador, Ueda scores maiden goal |url=https://english.kyodonews.net/news/2023/06/f1e5906388ff-football-japan-thrash-10-man-el-salvador-ueda-scores-maiden-goal.html |website=Kyodo News+ |access-date=25 August 2023 |date=15 June 2023}}</ref>

On 16 November 2023, Ueda scored his first international hat-trick during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – AFC second round|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match against [[Myanmar national football team|Myanmar]] in a 5–0 win.

In January 2024, he was part of the squad that participated in the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]] where he scored four goals in the tournament.

==Style of play==
[[Jimmy De Wulf]], Cercle Brugge's assistant manager described Ueda as a 'complete striker'. He has a strong finishing ability alongside a combination of pace, agility and above average jumping ability and strength given his smaller stature.<ref name="het-nieuwsblad">{{cite web |title=Heel Cercle Brugge is vol lof over Japans goudhaantje Ayase Ueda: "Hij haalt het beste uit zichzelf" |url=https://www.nieuwsblad.be/cnt/dmf20230417_96473513 |website=Het Nieuwsblad |access-date=25 August 2023 |language=nl-BE |date=18 April 2023}}</ref>

